Here's a Julia solution for your problem. I will use the Statistics package along with NamedTuple from Base. The function weather_data_analyzer takes as input an array of daily temperature data and returns a named tuple containing the average, max, min temperatures and trend based on the provided list.

```julia
using Statistics

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if isempty(temps)
        return (average=nothing, max=nothing, min=nothing, trend=nothing)
    end
    avg = mean(temps)
    max_temp = maximum(temps)
    min_temp = minimum(temps)

    if avg > max_temp 
        return (average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:decreasing)
    elseif avg < min_temp 
        return (average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:increasing)
    else
        return (average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:stable)
    end
end
```
This function first checks if the input list is empty. If it's empty, it returns a named tuple with all values set to nothing. If not, it calculates the mean (average), maximum and minimum temperatures of the data and determines the trend based on whether the average temperature is greater than or less than either the max or min temperature. It then constructs and returns the named tuple containing these calculated statistics.
